From: donadio@mxd120.rh.psu.edu (Matthew Donadio)
Subject: Re: Linux Consortium
Date: 29 Nov 1993 00:39:24 GMT

I didn't pay much attention to this on the mailing list, but I have
thought about this for a while and have a few points.

1.  IMHO, Linux is not really meant for inexperienced users.  Just
about everything for it is still ALPHA or BETA and is, to an extent,
crash prone.

2.  Who will have the time and resources to fully test a distribution?
The people doing this would more or less need a spare PC to do
everything.

3.  I don't really think the consortium would have much power.

I have said this many times before, and I am going to repeat myself.
All the distributions are too damn big.  They try to install too much
at once.  What is needed is a good _base_ package with what is needed
to have a useable system.  I think the following would be sufficient:
        The kernel
        Bash
        The GNU fileutils
        The GNU shellutils
        The GNU textutils
        The GNU diffutils
        Emacs
        The grep family
        GCC, libc, make, patch, m4, et al.
        Gawk
        Groff
        Gzip
        Perl
        Sed
        Tar
        The net-2 (network, that is) tree
        Kermit
        And the linux specific /etc and /bin utils

And I probably missed a few things.  Trying to include all the
compilers/interpreters, TeX, X, the X contrib, etc. is really stupid.
After people can add what they need.  The days of porting software is
gone; most things just need 'make' or some trivial changes.  I
compiled almost all of the above without any problems (perl gave me
trouble).  A lot of the BSD NET-2 tree compiles without trouble once
you install pmake.  The really big stuff (XFree86, Emacs, GCC, TeX) is
already compiled and ususally just needs 'tar xvfz'.  If people would
actually take some time and try to understand their system and install
what they need instead of grabbing every new toy, then there would be
fewer problems...

--
Beaker aka Matt Donadio   | Life is short,     ---   __ o    __~o    __ o
donadio@mxd120.rh.psu.edu |    ride like    ----    _`\<,   _`\<,   _`\<,
--- Penn State Cycling ---|      the wind.    ---  ( )/( ) ( )/( ) ( )/( )

